Note: You don't necessarily have to have all three to get a great shot, but they each have a contribution to make.

Different types of shots are:
Star trails
Any star trail photography will take from several minutes to several hours, depending on what you want, where you are, and what type of equipment you are using. Having a digital camera does not preclude you from being able to do 'astrophotography'. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/aa\/440830-3b3.jpg\/v4-460px-440830-3b3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/aa\/440830-3b3.jpg\/v4-760px-440830-3b3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Look into finding tutorials addressing the type of camera that you have. Light trails (traffic and light painting){"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/68\/440830-3b5.jpg\/v4-459px-440830-3b5.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/68\/440830-3b5.jpg\/v4-759px-440830-3b5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

With light trails, you can take the often times, ugly, light pollution and do something creative with it at night using long exposures. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/22\/440830-3b6.JPG\/v4-460px-440830-3b6.JPG","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/22\/440830-3b6.JPG\/v4-760px-440830-3b6.JPG","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Take your camera out of full manual mode and start experimenting with shutter speeds. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/16\/440830-3b7.JPG\/v4-459px-440830-3b7.JPG","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/16\/440830-3b7.JPG\/v4-759px-440830-3b7.JPG","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Cave photography is not for the faint of heart. Not only are you dealing with very closed in spaces, but those closed in spaces are pretty dark! If you are not an experienced caver, do not go into a cave alone. Even if you are, be sure to bring someone along for safety. Christmas pictures taken by the light of the tree{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/31\/440830-3b9.JPG\/v4-459px-440830-3b9.JPG","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/31\/440830-3b9.JPG\/v4-759px-440830-3b9.JPG","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Late night athletic events
Evening birthday parties
Sunrise or sunset is a great time to get beautiful pictures. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2a\/440830-3b12.JPG\/v4-459px-440830-3b12.JPG","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2a\/440830-3b12.JPG\/v4-759px-440830-3b12.JPG","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>\nLicense: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Once you have reached a certain comfort level and skill level, try something else. Start with a low ISO (100, 200, whatever your camera might allow, an aperture of about F20 (pretty small) and shoot for a few seconds, using the 'Bulb' feature. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/440830-4b1.JPG/v4-459px-440830-4b1.JPG","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/440830-4b1.JPG/v4-759px-440830-4b1.JPG","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Start with a higher ISO, open up your aperture a bit, and shorten the time. Depending on your camera, find a way to hold open the shutter. You might have to use a remote to start and finish it, a cable release, or computer software. But all, long exposure shots will have to have a tripod. Most, if not all, businesses, and most especially computer/digital items, have an Internet presence these days. Find their website and see if you can find any information on your particular type of camera. Also, to get increased exposure time, you will need to decrease your aperture (F20 or higher). You will get greater depth of field and more exposure time. Try doing this at several times of exposure using whatever method your camera manufacturer suggests. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ad/440830-4b3.JPG/v4-459px-440830-4b3.JPG","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ad/440830-4b3.JPG/v4-759px-440830-4b3.JPG","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
